<p>President-elect Barack Obama is said to be likely to name <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steven_Chu">Steven Chu</a>, the physicist who runs <a href="http://www.lbl.gov/">Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory</a>, as energy secretary.</p>
<p>Here are two things I like about this: (1) Chu believes science is real. (2) Chu believes climate change is real. <a href="http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1997/chu-autobio.html">Chu won</a> the 1997 Nobel Prize in physics. If you were at a Christmas party with him and the topic of discussion shifted to atomic physics, he would pwn your ass real fast.</p>
<p>But he is not a politician. This fact worries some in Washington, because one of his first and most important tasks in early 2009 will be a landmark energy reform bill. More: <a href="http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/12/10/obama.energy/index.html">CNN</a>, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/05/us/politics/05web-chu.html">NY Times</a>, <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/vcCandidateFeed2/idUSTRE4B970320081210">Reuters</a>.</p>
<p>VIDEO: Chu speaking about "A New Energy Program," at the <em>Climate Change and Global Politics Conference</em> hosted by the World Affairs Council of Northern California.</p>
<p><font color="red">UPDATE</font>: Boing Boing pal <a href="http://bartnagel.com">Bart Nagel</a>, who is a fine, fine photographer, shot <a href="http://bartnagel.com/series/chu.html">this great portrait of Chu</a> not long ago.</p>
